## 6. Model Design

### 6.1 Candidate Models

| Model | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Logistic Regression | Fast, interpretable, low latency | Cannot capture non-linear interactions |
| Gradient Boosted Trees (LightGBM / XGBoost) | Handles tabular data well, fast to train | Hard to capture high-order feature interactions |
| Wide & Deep (Google, 2016) | Combines memorization (wide) + generalization (deep) | More complex to train and serve |
| DeepFM | Learns pairwise and higher-order feature interactions automatically | Heavier at serving time |
| Two-Tower Model | Scales to millions of candidates via approximate nearest neighbor | Less accurate than full cross-attention models |

### 6.2 Recommended Architecture: Wide & Deep + GBDT Ensemble

- Use **LightGBM** as a strong baseline and for feature importance analysis
- Promote to **Wide & Deep** or **DeepFM** for production if offline metrics justify the latency tradeoff
- Use **calibration layer** (Platt scaling or isotonic regression) on top of the model output to ensure predicted probabilities are well-calibrated

### 6.3 Loss Function

Binary cross-entropy (log loss):

```
Loss = -[y * log(p) + (1-y) * log(1-p)]
```

Optionally: **Focal Loss** to down-weight easy negatives and focus training on hard examples.

