## 13. A/B Testing & Rollout Strategy

```
New model trained and validated offline
        ↓
Shadow mode: new model scores requests in parallel but doesn't affect serving
  → Compare offline predictions between old and new model
        ↓
Canary rollout: serve new model to 1–5% of traffic
  → Monitor latency, CTR, error rate
        ↓
A/B test: 50/50 split between old and new model
  → Run for minimum 1–2 weeks (to cover weekly seasonality)
  → Analyze CTR, RPM, CVR with statistical significance (p < 0.05)
        ↓
Full rollout if metrics are neutral or positive
        ↓
Old model kept on standby for 24–48hrs for quick rollback
```

---

## 14. Key Challenges & Trade-offs

| Challenge | Trade-off / Solution |
|---|---|
| **Latency vs Accuracy** | A more complex model (DeepFM) may improve AUC by 0.5% but add 30ms latency — evaluate if business impact justifies the cost |
| **Exploration vs Exploitation** | Always serving the highest pCTR ad means we never explore new ads. Use epsilon-greedy or contextual bandits to balance |
| **Cold Start (new user)** | No history → use demographic defaults, popular ads, or content-based signals |
| **Cold Start (new ad)** | No historical CTR → use advertiser-level CTR, category-level CTR as prior |
| **Position Bias** | Ads shown at top get more clicks by default. Use position debiasing during training |
| **Concept Drift** | User interests and ad trends change over time. Mitigate with frequent retraining and higher weight on recent data |
| **Training-Serving Skew** | Features computed differently offline vs online lead to silent model degradation. Log features at serving time and use them for training |

